issue.title: Implémentation du module de détection de maladies des plantes
issue.body:
## Description

Ce PR implémente le module de détection de maladies des plantes pour le système de surveillance agricole en Rust. Il s'agit du premier module du système qui servira de base pour les autres modules de prédiction.

### Fonctionnalités implémentées

- **Structure du projet** avec workspace Cargo
- **Module commun** pour les fonctionnalités partagées entre tous les modules
- **Module de détection de maladies** avec:
  - Modèle Random Forest pour les données de capteurs
  - Modèle CNN pour les images
  - Types et utilitaires pour la détection de maladies
- **API web** avec endpoints pour la détection de maladies
- **Documentation** et fichiers de configuration

### Architecture

Le projet est organisé en un workspace Cargo avec plusieurs crates:
- **common**: Fonctionnalités partagées entre tous les modules
- **disease_detection**: Détection de maladies des plantes
- **api**: API web pour accéder aux fonctionnalités

### Technologies utilisées

- **Rust**: Langage de programmation principal
- **Cargo**: Gestionnaire de paquets et système de build
- **Actix-web**: Framework web pour l'API
- **Diesel**: ORM pour l'accès à la base de données PostgreSQL
- **tch-rs**: Bindings PyTorch pour les modèles CNN
- **linfa**: Framework de machine learning pour les modèles classiques

### Comment tester

1. Cloner le dépôt
2. Exécuter le script d'initialisation: `./init.sh`
3. Lancer l'API: `cargo run -p api`
4. Tester les endpoints avec curl:

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/disease-detection/sensor \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "latitude": 48.8566,
    "longitude": 2.3522,
    "soil_moisture": 35.5,
    "air_humidity": 65.2,
    "temperature": 22.3,
    "soil_ph": 6.8,
    "nitrogen": 120.5,
    "phosphorus": 45.2,
    "potassium": 200.1
  }'
```

### Prochaines étapes

- Implémentation des autres modules de prédiction
- Ajout de tests unitaires et d'intégration
- Amélioration des modèles de prédiction
- Ajout de fonctionnalités d'authentification et d'autorisation

pull_request.title: 🎨 B2B Frontend Transformation: Regional Browsing + Lot Creation + QR Pickup
pull_request.body:
## 🎨 B2B Marketplace Frontend Transformation

This PR completes the frontend transformation from collectibles auctions to a hyperlocal B2B surplus marketplace, implementing the core user workflows for business equipment, construction materials, and commercial goods.

### 🚀 **New Pages & Features**

**Homepage Transformation** (`Index.tsx`)
- ✅ B2B-focused hero section with regional market emphasis
- ✅ Business equipment categories (Construction, Restaurant, Office, Municipal)
- ✅ "Find Lots Near You" with location-based browsing
- ✅ Success stories from local businesses

**Regional Browsing** (`RegionPage.tsx`)
- ✅ Distance-based filtering (5, 15, 30+ miles)
- ✅ Hyperlocal lot discovery with PostGIS integration
- ✅ Business verification tier badges (T0-T3)
- ✅ Real-time location detection and region selection

**Lot Creation** (`CreateLotPage.tsx`)
- ✅ Comprehensive B2B lot creation form
- ✅ Business-specific fields (condition, dimensions, specifications)
- ✅ Category selection for target verticals
- ✅ Pickup location and timeframe settings
- ✅ Reserve pricing and auction duration controls

**QR Scanner** (`QRScannerPage.tsx`)
- ✅ Camera-based QR code scanning for pickup verification
- ✅ Manual code entry fallback option
- ✅ Integration with pickup confirmation Edge Function
- ✅ Automatic seller payout trigger

**Updated Routing** (`App.tsx`)
- ✅ `/r/:regionSlug` - Regional marketplace browsing
- ✅ `/sell/new` - Create new B2B lot
- ✅ `/pickup/:lotId/scan` - QR pickup verification
- ✅ `/browse` - General browsing with location filters

### 🏗️ **Key Transformations**

**From Collectibles → B2B Surplus:**
- Auction timing: Live events → Always-on soft-close auctions
- Inventory: TCG/LEGO → Business equipment & materials  
- Audience: Collectors → Local businesses & contractors

![medium](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/medium-priority.svg)

The new `process_filter` function is a great step towards simplifying the filter logic. However, its current `if/elseif` structure is rigid and doesn't allow for combining filter criteria, such as filtering by both `from` and `subject`. This has led to a "Special cases" section for filters that need this combined logic.

To make the filtering more powerful and eliminate the need for special cases, you could refactor `process_filter` to build the filter criteria dynamically by chaining them. This would make the configuration more consistent and easier to maintain.

With a more flexible `process_filter`, you could integrate the special cases into your `gmail_filters` table, for example:
`{from = 'noreply@speedpay.com', subject = 'Chattanooga Gas', to = "Keep/Notifications/Chattanooga Gas"}`

```
local function process_filter(account, from_folder, from_address, to_folder, subject_pattern, body_pattern)
    local messages = account[from_folder]
    local has_criteria = from_address or subject_pattern or body_pattern

    if from_address then
        messages = messages:contain_from(from_address)
    end
    if subject_pattern then
        messages = messages:match_subject(subject_pattern)
    end
    if body_pattern then
        messages = messages:match_body(body_pattern)
    end

    if has_criteria then
        messages:move_messages(account[to_folder])
    end
end
```

<!-- Guidelines: https://docs.spacestation14.io/en/getting-started/pr-guideline -->

## About the PR
I made moths take less _extra_ damage from being on-fire (_not_ to be confused with their base heat weakness) to give them time to react, and to make it more fair for them compared to everyone else.
This should give moths roughly twice the time to react upon being set on fire.

## Why / Balance
This has been changed due to moths having an extremely easily abused weakness to flames; any raider or traitor could pick bartender, grab a bottle or two of alcohol, and set fire to every moth they see, killing them within *5s*, with little they could do about it once they realised what was happening.

This also posed an unfair disadvantage to combat roles, as even a moth HoS or Captain could be *very* easily killed with just 20u of napalm, made with easily acquired materials at no cost.

## Technical details
I just changed;
  - type: Flammable
    damage:
      types:
        Heat: 4.5 # moths burn more easily
        
to;

  - type: Flammable
    damage:
      types:
        Heat: 2 # moths burn more easily
        
## Media
Unchanged, upstream example;

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2fb1c589-7db7-4f92-bd29-674224fdab0e

New, PR example; (please note I accidentally gave the human urist an extra spray)

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/19746dfb-5e29-4bea-9f6c-69acc2f2b18f
